A few things I’ve learned since moving into my new home 

1. Buy a laser level. That’s the tip, just buy it 
2. Invest in pieces you feel represent YOU- now and in a year from now 
3. Take your time putting things away. Throw shit out that doesn’t spark joy or whatever that lady said 
4. YOU GOT FOOD AT HOME. I actually love cooking so I have enjoyed buying groceries that fuel ME. Trying new recipes in my new kitchen is self-care 
5. It has to feel like you otherwise you won’t see the journey it took to get there. Don’t try to make old styles, old layouts or even old art work in a new space. Your new space aesthetic needs to fit YOU now. If it takes you selling everything, saving up or even starting from scratch- do that. 

〰 my amazon storefront linked has tons of stuff I loved on there. Thank you for all the kind words during this transition for me 🖤

Welcoming ease even if it requires effort. 
Welcoming peace even if it requires pain 

My life has changed so much in the last 6 months. I welcome everything I am meant to have in the next 6 months. I’m just getting started

Home on a Sunday. 

It’s noon and I’m walking around looking well rested. Love it here.

You can find me at the intersection of peace and purpose. Across from persistence, next door to love

To live creatively.. I’m truth, in confidence, in an unapologetic sense of self. To cultivate the same fullness and joy that I see when I am behind the scenes- that’s where I’m at. Come find me.

At this phase in my life where I only want the best for me. 
And my “best” is unique. It doesn’t look like yours. Happiness isn’t a cut and paste opportunity. My best feels good. It amplifies me in the brightest of ways. 

7 months ago I asked God to help me live in my purpose. I asked God to remove everything and everyone who wasn’t in position to support the highest version of myself, my creativity, my happiness, my health. Over the last few months, dead ends and empty relationships have been falling off and out of my life. Instead of feeling rejected- I feel grateful for the redirection and realignment.

You deserve in thrive in spaces, places and people that support the highest version of yourself. As people get removed, as opportunities end- don’t be surprised. They were never meant to come to the next chapter with you anyway. 

Keep thriving. 

Xoxo

Sunday afternoon, a love story ✨

In life, I believe we have a few core lessons we are destined to learn. 

These core lessons are unique to each individual depending upon the path you are supposed to take in life. God (or the universe, whatever floats your raft) .. we keep resurfacing these core lessons in your life UNTIL you learn them. 

These lessons may appear in different scenarios, with different themes, but ultimately- the lessons are the same. Since we have free will, your opportunities to overcome the lesson will be plenty. When you refuse to get it through your head- you will learn in the hardest of ways. 

〰The lesson sweetie, isn’t optional. How you learn it, may be.

For me- my lessons are 

Intuition: learning how to hear and trust my own

Being secure in what I KNOW without outside validation: don’t tell me it’s biscuits when I know it’s cornbread 

Pleasing me before pleasing you: pouring into my own cup first so I may approach others with overflow 

Taking up space: unapologetically, taking up space in who I am, what I’ve done, what I can be and what the hell I want. 

Existing outside of being “somebody’s”: can I vibrantly exist without being of ownership to someone or something else

My lessons, are deep. The way I’ve been learning them, often very ghetto. The positive? I can now see when a refresher course is resurfacing and I am more mindful to choose with intention and heart. 

Sunday afternoon reflections may be my fav.

“Grass growing through concrete is a courageous act. The grass never stops to consider the difficulty of its task. It does not seek advice or make plans. It has an inborn mission to grow. The grass does not consider all the possible ramifications of its actions, that it may be stepped on or ripped from its roots. The grass simply knows what it must do and does it, without question, hesitation, or complaint. When we are aware of our inborn mission and undertake that mission without doubt or fear, we become like the grass; courageous enough to do what is required of us despite the difficulty.” 

Be courageous enough to grow. Healthy enough to flourish
